0.description: Acadia National Park protects the natural beauty of the highest rocky headlands along the Atlantic coastline of the United States, an abundance of habitats, and a rich cultural heritage. At 3.5 million visits a year, it's one of the top 10 most-visited national parks in the United States. Visitors enjoy 27 miles of historic motor roads, 158 miles of hiking trails, and 45 miles of carriage roads.

1.description: Visit Arches to discover a landscape of contrasting colors, land forms, and textures unlike any other in the world. The park has over 2,000 natural stone arches and hundreds of soaring pinnacles, massive rock fins, and giant balanced rocks. This red-rock wonderland will amaze you with its formations, refresh you with its trails, and inspire you with its sunsets.

2.description: The rugged beauty of the Badlands draws visitors from around the world. These striking geologic deposits contain one of the world’s richest fossil beds. Ancient horses and rhinos once roamed here. The park’s 244,000 acres protect an expanse of mixed-grass prairie where bison, bighorn sheep, prairie dogs, and black-footed ferrets live today.

4.description: Within sight of downtown Miami, yet worlds away, Biscayne protects a rare combination of aquamarine waters, emerald islands, and fish-bejeweled coral reefs. Evidence of 10,000 years of human history is here too, from pirates and shipwrecks to pineapple farmers and presidents. Outdoors enthusiasts can boat, snorkel, camp, watch wildlife…or simply relax in a rocking chair gazing out over the bay.

6.description: Hoodoos (irregular columns of rock) exist on every continent, but here is the largest concentration found anywhere on Earth. Situated along a high plateau at the top of the Grand Staircase, the park's high elevations include numerous life communities, fantastic dark skies, and geological wonders that defy description.

7.description: Canyonlands invites you to explore a wilderness of countless canyons and fantastically formed buttes carved by the Colorado River and its tributaries. Rivers divide the park into four districts: Island in the Sky, The Needles, The Maze, and the rivers themselves. These areas share a primitive desert atmosphere, but each offers different opportunities for sightseeing and adventure.

10.description: Channel Islands National Park encompasses five remarkable islands and their ocean environment, preserving and protecting a wealth of natural and cultural resources. Isolation over thousands of years has created unique animals, plants, and archeological resources found nowhere else on Earth and helped preserve a place where visitors can experience coastal southern California as it once was.

11.description: Astonishing biodiversity exists in Congaree National Park, the largest intact expanse of old growth bottomland hardwood forest remaining in the southeastern United States. Waters from the Congaree and Wateree Rivers sweep through the floodplain, carrying nutrients and sediments that nourish and rejuvenate this ecosystem and support the growth of national and state champion trees.

12.description: Crater Lake inspires awe. Native Americans witnessed its formation 7,700 years ago, when a violent eruption triggered the collapse of a tall peak. Scientists marvel at its purity: fed by rain and snow, it’s the deepest lake in the USA and one of the most pristine on earth. Artists, photographers, and sightseers gaze in wonder at its blue water and stunning setting atop the Cascade Mountain Range.

13.description: Though a short distance from the urban areas of Cleveland and Akron, Cuyahoga Valley National Park seems worlds away. The park is a refuge for native plants and wildlife, and provides routes of discovery for visitors. The winding Cuyahoga River gives way to deep forests, rolling hills, and open farmlands. Walk or ride the Towpath Trail to follow the historic route of the Ohio & Erie Canal.

14.description: In this below-sea-level basin, steady drought and record summer heat make Death Valley a land of extremes. Yet, each extreme has a striking contrast. Towering peaks are frosted with winter snow. Rare rainstorms bring vast fields of wildflowers. Lush oases harbor tiny fish and refuge for wildlife and humans. Despite its morbid name, a great diversity of life survives in Death Valley.

15.description: Denali is six million acres of wild land, bisected by one ribbon of road. Travelers along it see the relatively low-elevation taiga forest give way to high alpine tundra and snowy mountains, culminating in North America's tallest peak, 20,310' Denali. Wild animals large and small roam un-fenced lands, living as they have for ages. Solitude, tranquility and wilderness await.

16.description: Almost 70 miles (113 km) west of Key West lies the remote Dry Tortugas National Park. This 100-square mile park is mostly open water with seven small islands. Accessible only by boat or seaplane, the park is known the world over as the home of magnificent Fort Jefferson, picturesque blue waters, superlative coral reefs and marine life, and the vast assortment of bird life that frequents the area.

17.description: Everglades National Park protects an unparalleled landscape that provides important habitat for numerous rare and endangered species like the manatee, American crocodile, and the elusive Florida panther. An international treasure as well - a World Heritage Site, International Biosphere Reserve, a Wetland of International Importance, and a specially protected area under the Cartagena Treaty.

22.description: Located in Arizona, Grand Canyon National Park encompasses 277 miles (446 km) of the Colorado River and adjacent uplands. The park is home to much of the immense Grand Canyon; a mile (1.6 km) deep, and up to 18 miles (29 km) wide. Layered bands of colorful rock reveal millions of years of geologic history. Grand Canyon is unmatched in the incomparable vistas it offers visitors from the rim.

30.description: Hot Springs National Park has a rich cultural past. Ancient thermal springs, mountain views, incredible geology, forested hikes, and abundant creeks – all in the middle of town – make Hot Springs National Park a unique and beautiful destination.

Dark night skies, a rich cultural history, and surreal geologic features add to the wonder of this vast wilderness in southern California. Come explore for yourself.

34.description: A landscape is alive underneath our feet, filled with creatures that remind us what it is to be wild. Katmai was established in 1918 to protect the volcanically devastated region surrounding Novarupta and the Valley of Ten Thousand Smokes. Today, Katmai National Park and Preserve also protects 9,000 years of human history and important habitat for salmon and thousands of brown bears.

35.description: At the edge of the Kenai Peninsula lies a land where the ice age lingers. Nearly 40 glaciers flow from the Harding Icefield, Kenai Fjords' crowning feature. Wildlife thrives in icy waters and lush forests around this vast expanse of ice. Sugpiaq people relied on these resources to nurture a life entwined with the sea. Today, shrinking glaciers bear witness to the effects of our changing climate.

images.caption: A stroll to Glacier View provides a nice overlook of Exit Glacier as part of a 1 mile accessible walk.

36.description: Caribou, sand dunes, the Kobuk River, Onion Portage - just some of the facets of Kobuk Valley National Park. Half a million caribou migrate through, their tracks crisscrossing sculpted dunes. The Kobuk River is an ancient and current path for people and wildlife. For 9000 years, people came to Onion Portage to harvest caribou as they swam the river. Even today, that rich tradition continues.

images.title: Kobuk Sand Dunes
images.altText: sun setting on sand dunes
images.caption: The setting sun casts shadows of black spruce on the dunes and colors the water of Ahnewetut Creek a deep blue.

images.title: Mountains as Far as the Eye Can See
images.altText: aerial view of snow capped mountains
images.caption: The peaks of the Baird Mountains stretch far into the distance and are so remote that many of them have not been named.

images.title: Left Behind
images.altText: Caribou bone sitting in the sand
images.caption: Caribou migrate across the Great Kobuk Sand Dunes, heading north in the summer and south in the fall. Some survive and some don't, which is a reality of life

images.title: Lone Rangifer tarandus
images.altText: Single caribou with antlers in velvet
images.caption: A single caribou of the 240,000+ strong Western Arctic herd on its fall migration south across Kobuk Valley National Park.

images.title: Kobuk Locoweed
images.altText: pink flower growing in sand
images.caption: Oxytropis kobukensis (Kobuk Locoweed) is a member of the pea family and adds a splash of pink to the sand dunes. The blossoms have that typical pea/ bean flower shape that many gardeners know.

37.description: Lake Clark National Park and Preserve is a land of stunning beauty. Volcanoes steam, salmon run, bears forage, and craggy mountains reflect in shimmering turquoise lakes. Here, too, local people and culture still depend on the land and water. Venture into the park to become part of the wilderness.

images.title: Lake Clark
images.altText: Photo of blue sky with fluffy white clouds reflect in calm lake with mountains in the background.
images.caption: The park's namesake lake is the largest lake by volume in the National Park Service.

images.title: Tanalian Falls
images.altText: Waterfall surrounded by forest in fall foiliage and mountains in the background.
images.caption: The park protects thousands of waterfalls including Tanalian Falls, which is a popular day hike destination from the town of Port Alsworth.

images.title: Redoubt Volcano
images.altText: Photo of a stratovolcano flanked with glaciers towering over a river valley.
images.caption: Lake Clark is a land of fire and ice. Active volcanism and retreating glaciers created and continue to shape the peaks, moraines, and river systems in the Chigmit and Neacola Mountains.

images.title: Tanaina Glacier
images.altText: photo of large alpine glacier
images.caption: Perenial snow and glacial ice covers ~1,250 square miles, or 20% of Lake Clark National Park and Preserve.

images.title: Two cubs playing at Silver Salmon Creek
images.altText: two brown bear cubs playing in the sedges
images.caption: Bear viewing is a popular activity along the Cook Inlet Coast.

images.title: Boreal Forest
images.altText: Forest of spruce trees blanketed in snow and fog.
images.caption: Boreal forests encircle the earth's northern latitudes like an emerald necklace. Lake Clark's forest, which covers more than 440 thousand acres or 11% of the park,  is dominated by white spruce mixed with black spruce and birch.

images.title: Telaquana Lake
images.altText: A colorful sky, an island with spruce trees, and mountains in the background reflect in a calm lake
images.caption: A number of glacier fed lakes pepper the western boundary of the Chigmit and Neacola mountains like a string of spectacular turquoise gems.

images.title: West Glacier Creek
images.altText: Photo of a river delta flowing into tidal flats surrounded by green salt marshes and mountains.
images.caption: Estuaries where rivers meet the sea provide a mosaic of rich habitats along the Cook Inlet Coast that support high numbers of bears and other wildlife.

images.title: Richard L. Proenneke National Historic Site
images.altText: Photo of a one story log cabin, cache, forest, and American flag reflecting in a calm, blue lake.
images.caption: The park protects and interprets the Richard L. Proenneke National Historic Site and trail complex as a symbol of the national wilderness movement and a source of inspiration and solace sought out by visitors from throughout the world.

38.description: Lassen Volcanic National Park is home to steaming fumaroles, meadows freckled with wildflowers, clear mountain lakes, and numerous volcanoes. Jagged peaks tell the story of its eruptive past while hot water continues to shape the land.

images.title: Winter at Manzanita Lake
images.altText: A frozen lake below snow-covered trees and peak
images.caption: With over 30 feet of snowfall annually, Lassen provides numerous opportunities for winter recreation.

images.title: Hat Creek
images.altText: Golden grasses edge a pond reflecting a snow-dusted peak
images.caption: Lassen Volcanic's rugged volcanic landscape is softened by numerous meadows, lakes, and creeks.

images.title: Bumpass Hell
images.altText: A boardwalk passes through a colorful, steaming hydrothermal basin.
images.caption: A 3-mile round-trip trail leads to Bumpass Hell, the largest of the park's hydrothermal areas.

images.title: Brokeoff Panorama
images.altText: Two hikers sit on a mountain top with a view of multiple peaks, dotted with patches of snow
images.caption: Over 150 miles of trails let you choose your adventure.

images.title: Deep Blue
images.altText: A volcanic peak rises above a tree-lined, deep blue lake.
images.caption: Lassen Peak stands out boldly between the bright blue sky and the sapphire hue of Lake Helen.

images.title: A Fisherman's Paradise
images.altText: A fisherman casts a line from a boat below a snow-dotted volcanic peak.
images.caption: Manzanita Lake offers spectacular catch-and-release fishing in the shadow of volcanoes.

images.title: Lassen Peak Eruption
images.altText: An ash cloud rises above a volcano with an early 19th century vehicle at the forefront.
images.caption: A large, explosive eruption of Lassen Peak brought national attention and set the stage for the establishment of Lassen Peak.

39.description: Rolling hills, deep river valleys, and the worlds longest known cave system. Mammoth Cave National Park is home to thousands of years of human history and a rich diversity of plant and animal life, earning it the title of UNESCO World Heritage Site and International Biosphere Reserve.

images.title: Broadway in Mammoth Cave
images.altText: A ranger explains the cave to visitors in the vast expanse of the passage called Broadway.
images.caption: A ranger explains Mammoth Cave in the vast passage known as Broadway. Rotunda, one of the cave's largest rooms, is just ahead.

images.title: Mammoth Cave - Dripstone Wall
images.altText: Dripstone formations create a panoply of textures in the Frozen Niagara section of Mammoth Cave
images.caption: Dripstone formations create a panoply of textures in the Frozen Niagara section of Mammoth Cave as slowly dripping water redeposits dissolved limestone over the course of centuries. Image is a panoramic composite.

images.title: Wonder in Mammoth Cave
images.altText: A girl peers wonderingly into the shadows of Mammoth Cave.
images.caption: Mammoth Cave's shadows have beckoned the explorer deep within its visitors for geneerations, asking the question "Where does that lead? What lies in the dark places?" The questions remain as compelling today as they did for the first explorers.

images.title: Green River in Mammoth Cave National Park
images.altText: A kayaker paddles up the languid waters of the Green River in Mammoth Cave National Park.
images.caption: More than 30 miles of the Green and Nolin Rivers course through Mammoth Cave NP, representing one of the most biologically diverse river systems in the Eastern United States. Their languid waters are a magnet for canoeist, kayakers and anglers.

images.title: Fog at Mammoth Cave Entrance
images.altText: A layer of fog hangs over a small group gathered to enter Mammoth Cave on a summer day.
images.caption: A layer of mist hangs over a small tour group gathered at the Historic Entrance of Mammoth Cave on a summer day - it both delights the skin and fogs spectacles, and gives a sense that one is on the threshold of another world.

images.title: Frances Benjamin Johnston Enters Mammoth Cave in 1892
images.altText: Frances Benjamin Johnston and her photographic expedition enter Mammoth Cave in 1892.
images.caption: Frances Benjamin Johnston and her photographic expedition enter the Historic Entrance of Mammoth Cave, 1892.

40.description: Mesa Verde National Park was established in 1906 to preserve and interpret the archeological heritage of the Ancestral Pueblo people who made it their home for over 700 years, from 600 to 1300 CE. Today, the park protects nearly 5,000 known archeological sites, including 600 cliff dwellings. These sites are some of the most notable and best preserved in the United States.

images.title: Cliff Palace
images.altText: Large cliff dwelling in cliff alcove
images.caption: Cliff Palace, Mesa Verde's Largest Cliff Dwelling

images.title: Step House
images.altText: Park visitors visiting a cliff dwelling
images.caption: Visitors enjoying Step House, on Wetherill Mesa

images.title: Balcony House
images.altText: A cliff dwelling within a cliff alcove seen from across a canyon
images.caption: View of Balcony House from the Soda Canyon Overlook

images.title: Square Tower House
images.altText: View of cliff dwelling from above a canyon
images.caption: Square Tower House from overlook along the Mesa Top Loop

images.title: View of Spruce Tree House
images.altText: View of cliff dwelling from across canyon
images.caption: Spruce Tree House

images.title: Spruce Tree House
images.altText: Within a cliff dwelling
images.caption: Spruce Tree House, Mesa Verde's third largest and best preserved cliff dwelling

images.title: Mesa Verde Visitor and Research Center
images.altText: Visitor center entrance with sculpture of Ancestral Pueblo climber in front plaza.
images.caption: Stop by the Mesa Verde Visitor & Research Center at the park entrance where park staff will help you plan your visit.

41.description: Ascending to 14,410 feet above sea level, Mount Rainier stands as an icon in the Washington landscape. An active volcano, Mount Rainier is the most glaciated peak in the contiguous U.S.A., spawning five major rivers. Subalpine wildflower meadows ring the icy volcano while ancient forest cloaks Mount Rainier’s lower slopes. Wildlife abounds in the park’s ecosystems. A lifetime of discovery awaits.

images.title: Silver Forest Sunset
images.altText: A purple and pink streaked sky over a mountain peak and forested valley.
images.caption: The Silver Forest Trail at Sunrise features spectacular views of Mount Rainier and the White River valley.

images.title: Climbing Mount Rainier
images.altText: Climber on glacier steps downward with icy crags in background.
images.caption: Summiting Mount Rainier involves climbing a volcano, scaling glaciers, dealing with high elevations and much more. Almost 10,000 people a year attempt to summit.

images.title: Giants of the Old-Growth Forest
images.altText: Towering cedars and douglas-firs reach skyward while a beam of sun breaks through the canopy.
images.caption: With some of the few remaining old-growth forests in the Cascade Mountains, Mount Rainier National Park protects native plants great and small in places like the Grove of the Patriarchs.

images.title: Marmot in Morning Dew
images.altText: A hoary marmot with white frosted fur rests on a rock beside white flowers in a meadow.
images.caption: From small amphibians and hoary marmots to the black bears and elk, many animals call the wild places of Mount Rainier home.

images.title: Kids Hiking Through Wildflower Meadow
images.altText: Two children hike on trail through wildflower meadow with Mount Rainier above them.
images.caption: Enjoying the outdoors through recreation is a big part of many visitors' experiences.

images.title: Mount Rainier at sunset
images.altText: Sunset paints the glaciers of Mount Rainier in pink and gold.
images.caption: Every scenic overlook shows a different side of Mount Rainier. Viewed from Gobblers Knob Lookout at sunset, the glaciers covering the mountain turn pink and gold.

images.title: National Park Inn in Winter
images.altText: The historic National Park Inn covered in a foot of snow.
images.caption: For thousands of years, people have traveled up to, over, and around Mount Rainier. Today the park strives to preserve this history while providing a chance for new generations to find their own adventures.

images.title: Wildflower Meadow Along the Wonderland Trail
images.altText: Purple lupine and white bistort bloom in a meadow alongside a sign for the Wonderland Trail.
images.caption: Both the Wonderland Trail and subalpine meadows encircle Mount Rainier. Summertime blooms splatter the hillsides with color.

images.title: Mount Rainier from Aurora Lake
images.altText: A glaciated mountain framed by forested hillsides reflects in a still mountain lake.
images.caption: Aurora Lake in Klapatche Park on the west side of Mount Rainier.

42.description: The National Park of American Samoa welcomes you into the heart of the South Pacific, to a world of sights, sounds, and experiences that you will find in no other national park in the United States. Enjoy this unique national park and the welcoming people of American Samoa. We are here to protect its rich culture and natural resources. Come explore them with us!

images.title: Back side of Pola Island from Tuafanua Trail
images.altText: Tuafanua Trail
images.caption: Pola Island rises over 400 feet straight out of the ocean off Tutuila. A short walk from Vatia village, Pola is an ideal nesting site for many species of seabirds.

images.title: Ta'u Island
images.altText: Ta'u Island
images.caption: Si'u Point is a good place to view the south coast of Ta'u. some of the tallest sea cliffs in the world stairstep over 3,000 feet to the summit of Lata Mountain.

images.title: Ofu Island
images.altText: Ofu Island
images.caption: With a secluded sandy beach and fringing reef, Ofu unit of the park is an ideal place to snorkel or simply enjoy the solitude. The island of Olosega rises in the distance.

images.title: King Fisher bird
images.altText: King Fisher bird
images.caption: Birds are the most abundant and diverse animals in American Samoa, as they are on most oceanic islands.

43.fullName: National Parks of New York Harbor
43.description: These 11 sites preserve more than 400 years of American history! We invite you to explore the past and investigate its relevance in our lives today. From the birth of American democracy to the evolution of commerce, harbor defense, ecology and immigration, the breadth of themes commemorated through the National Parks of New York Harbor reflect the richness and diversity of our heritage.

images.title: Manhattan skyline as seen from Governors Island National Monument
images.altText: Manhattan skyline as seen from Governors Island National Monument
images.caption: National Parks of New York Harbor includes ten national parks, including six within Manhattan alone.

images.title: General Grant National Memorial at dusk in midwinter
images.altText: General Grant National Memorial at dusk in midwinter
images.caption: The largest mausoleum in North America pays tribute to Civil War general and U.S. President Ulysses S. Grant, who is entombed here with his wife Julia.

images.title: Battery Weed, Fort Wadsworth, Staten Island
images.altText: Battery Weed, Fort Wadsworth, Staten Island
images.caption: Gateway National Recreation Area covers two states and three New York City boroughs. Several of its sites are former military bases, such as Fort Wadsworth.

images.title: Statue of Liberty looking ahead
images.altText: Statue of Liberty looking ahead
images.caption: Statue of Liberty National Monument also includes Ellis Island Immigration Museum.

images.title: African Burial Ground National Monument
images.altText: African Burial Ground National Monument
images.caption: A vast cemetery for enslaved and free Africans, forgotten since the 1790s, was rediscovered in 1991.

44.fullName: New River Gorge National Park and Preserve
44.description: A rugged, whitewater river flowing northward through deep canyons, the New River is among the oldest rivers on the continent. The park encompasses over 70,000 acres of land along the New River, is rich in cultural and natural history, and offers an abundance of scenic and recreational opportunities.

images.title: Sunrise at Diamond Point
images.altText: sun rising over the New River Gorge
images.caption: Sun rising over the New River Gorge from Diamond Point on the Endless Wall Trail.

images.title: New River Gorge Bridge

images.caption: The New River Gorge Bridge spans across the New River.

images.caption: View from Turkey Spur at Grandview

images.altText: waterfall and stream
images.caption: Waterfall on Dowdy Creek

45.description: Less than three hours from Seattle, an alpine landscape beckons. Discover communities of life adapted to moisture in the west and recurring fire in the east. Explore jagged peaks crowned by more than 300 glaciers. Listen to cascading waters in forested valleys. Witness a landscape sensitive to the Earth's changing climate. Help steward the ecological heart of the Cascades.

images.title: Stehekin - Looking down Lake Chelan
images.altText: boats on the water with mountains and trees surrounding
images.caption: Stehekin sits at the top of Lake Chelan, welcoming visitors to take a life at a slower pace.

images.title: Camping on Ross Lake
images.altText: Tents set up in a wooded area.
images.caption: Grab your tent, your sleeping bag, and adventurous soul and camp along Ross Lake.

images.title: Pelton Basin from Cascade Pass
images.altText: Trees surround the frame with glacier and mountains in the background
images.caption: Let the wow factor exceed your expectations while hiking Cascade Pass.

images.title: Backpack the North Cascades
images.altText: Person with backpacking and climbing gear hikes on a trail.
images.caption: Explore the trails and backcountry camping and climbing in a landscape over 9,000 feet of vertical relief.

images.title: Jagged Mountain Peaks
images.altText: Jagged mountain peaks give way to glaciers.
images.caption: Explore jagged peaks crowned by more than 300 glaciers as you traverse the landscape.

46.description: With its incredible range of precipitation and elevation, diversity is the hallmark of Olympic National Park. Encompassing nearly a million acres, the park protects a vast wilderness, thousands of years of human history, and several distinctly different ecosystems, including glacier-capped mountains, old-growth temperate rain forests, and over 70 miles of wild coastline. Come explore!

images.title: Mountain Sunset
images.altText: Hikers sit and watch the sun set behind snow-capped mountains.
images.caption: Backpackers stop to enjoy a spectacular sunset in Olympic's high country.

images.title: Roosevelt Elk
images.altText: A herd of elk crossing a river.
images.caption: A herd of Roosevelt Elk cross a river in Olympic.

images.title: Tide Pools of the Olympic Coast
images.altText: Orange sea stars on a rocky coast.
images.caption: Ocher sea stars rest on the rocks during a low tide on one of Olympic's beaches.

images.caption: A fresh layer of snow covers Hurricane Ridge in the Olympic Mountains.

images.title: Olympic Forest
images.altText: Large trees and ferns
images.caption: Large trees and ferns inhabit the temperate forests of Olympic.

47.description: Park Hours: 8am to 5pm, MST Did you know that Petrified Forest is perfect for exploration and discovery? While the park has all the wonders known for a century, there are many new adventures and discoveries to share. There are backcountry hikes into areas never open before such as Red Basin. There are new exhibits that bring the stories to life. Come rediscover Petrified Forest!

images.caption: Sunrise and sunset are favorite times to view the colorful Painted Desert of the Petrified Forest National Wilderness Area

48.description: Some 23 million years ago multiple volcanoes erupted, flowed, and slid to form what would become Pinnacles National Park. What remains is a unique landscape. Travelers journey through chaparral, oak woodlands, and canyon bottoms. Hikers enter rare talus caves and emerge to towering rock spires teeming with life: prairie and peregrine falcons, golden eagles, and the inspiring California condor.

images.title: Balconies Caves
images.altText: Boulders in the Balconies Cave.
images.caption: Balconies Cliffs as seen from the inside of the Balconies Caves

images.title: Tree
images.altText: Light falling on tree
images.caption: Light illuminates a tree on a rainy day, seen from the Resurrection Wall.

images.title: Tarantula
images.altText: A Tarantula walking
images.caption: A Tarantula crawls in the wild.

images.title: High Peaks with Condors Above
images.altText: A massive rock spire with California condors flying above the peak.
images.caption: The best views of Pinnacles' rocks can be enjoyed from the west side with almost no effort required.

49.description: Rocky Mountain National Park’s 415 square miles encompass and protect spectacular mountain environments. Enjoy Trail Ridge Road – which crests at over 12,000 feet including many overlooks to experience the subalpine and alpine worlds – along with over 300 miles of hiking trails, wildflowers, wildlife, starry nights, and fun times. In a world of superlatives, Rocky is on top!

images.title: Summer on the Tundra
images.altText: Yellow flowers bloom on tundra slopes with mountains in the background.
images.caption: Old Man of the Mountain bloom on Rocky's alpine tundra.

images.title: Trail Ridge Road
images.altText: Road sweeps across open tundra with mountains in background.
images.caption: Trail Ridge Road, the highest continuous paved road in the United States, let's visitors experience Rocky's alpine tundra.

images.title: Elk in Moraine Park
images.altText: A herd of elk stand in a meadow.
images.caption: In the fall, Rocky's elk gather together in groups for the mating season.

images.title: Horseshoe Park
images.altText: The moon sets below mountain peaks at sunrise.
images.caption: While the moon sets, the sun rises at Horseshoe Park, one of Rocky's beautiful meadows.

images.title: Longs Peak
images.altText: Longs Peak, covered in snow, against dark moody clouds.
images.caption: Longs Peak towers above Rocky Mountain National Park.

50.description: Tucson, Arizona is home to the nation's largest cacti. The giant saguaro is the universal symbol of the American west. These majestic plants, found only in a small portion of the United States, are protected by Saguaro National Park, to the east and west of the modern city of Tucson. Here you have a chance to see these enormous cacti, silhouetted by the beauty of a magnificent desert sunset.

images.title: Saguaro Flowers
images.altText: Saguaro flowers
images.caption: The flowering season in Saguaro National Park attracts visitors from all over the world.

images.title: Flowering Fishhook Pincushion Cactus
images.altText: A flowering fishhook pincushion cactus
images.caption: Wildflower season at Saguaro National Park is at it's peak in the month of MArch. The Pincushion cactus, however, blooms April through August.

images.title: Coyote Pups
images.altText: Two coyote pups captured on a wilderness camera
images.caption: Saguaro National Park has a vast variety of wildlife, and with the help of wilderness cameras, can be photographed to help with studies and for visitors to learn about animals only seen by chance.

images.title: Saguaro National Park Lighting Storm
images.altText: Lightning strike captured on camera with saguaros in the background
images.caption: Saguaro deaths are usually attributed to natural weather conditions and other natural phenomena. Specifically, lightning strikes have been known to strike saguaros due to the large amount of water stored within their fleshy tissue.

images.title: Weather at Saguaro National Park
images.altText: Rare Sight of snow in Saguaro National Park East Visitor Center (Rincon Mountain District)
images.caption: Saguaro National Park summers can be extremely hot with temperatures exceeding 105 degrees F, lows averaging 72 degrees F.  Winters are mild warm days averaging 65 degrees F and cool nights averaging 40 degrees F. Snowfall is extremely rare in the area.

images.title: Group of Regal Horned Lizards
images.altText: A group of Phrynosoma solare, or regal horned lizards.
images.caption: Regal horned lizards are one of many reptiles in the park, who have adapted to living in the harsh desert environment. Information on how different species survive can be found on the park's website, visitor center, or through our many programs offered.

51.description: This dramatic landscape testifies to nature's size, beauty, and diversity—huge mountains, rugged foothills, deep canyons, vast caverns, and the world's largest trees. The parks lie side by side in the southern Sierra Nevada east of the San Joaquin Valley. Weather varies a lot by season and elevation, which ranges from 1,370' to 14,494'.

images.title: Kings Canyon
images.altText: A deep canyon with a forested floor and steep granite cliffs
images.caption: The Glaciers carved the Kings Canyon's steep granite cliffs, leaving a wide U-shaped valley.

images.title: The Tablelands
images.altText: A steep granite slope leads from forest to a bare alpine landscape
images.caption: Just above Lodgepole Valley, the trail to the Watchtower offers views above the treeline.

images.title: Moro Rock
images.altText: A guardrail encircles people along a narrow walkway with wide views
images.caption: A historic stairway leads to the top of Moro Rock, offering views from foothills to peaks

images.title: Giant Sequoia in Winter
images.altText: A giant sequoia's reddish bark contrasts with the snow around it
images.caption: For those who don't mind icy roads, winter offers stunning views of sequoias in snow.

images.title: Giant Forest Museum
images.altText: A rustic building is surrounded by giant sequoias
images.caption: Giant Forest Museum offers exhibits, park information, and a bookstore.

52.description: Just 75 miles from the bustle of Washington, D.C., Shenandoah National Park is a land bursting with cascading waterfalls, spectacular vistas, fields of wildflowers, and quiet wooded hollows. With over 200,000 acres of protected lands that are haven to deer, songbirds, and black bear, there's so much to explore...and your journey begins right here!

images.title: Adventure Awaits
images.altText: A man stands on a rocky outcrop overlooking the receding mountains.
images.caption: There are over 60 peaks with an elevation over 3,000 feet in Shenandoah.

images.title: Wonderful Waterfalls
images.altText: A man stands with his back facing us, looking at a waterfall.
images.caption: Dark Hollow Falls, at 70 feet, is our most visited waterfall.

images.title: Red-Bellied Woodpecker
images.altText: A close up shot of a Red-Bellied Woodpecker with a blurry teal background.
images.caption: There are over 200 species of bird that call Shenandoah "home."

images.title: Driving on Skyline Drive
images.altText: A road surrounded by fall foliage turns a curve around a small waterfall.
images.caption: There are 105 miles to explore on Skyline Drive.

images.title: Find Yourself in Nature
images.altText: Looking up at a poplar stand canopy, which is turning yellow in fall.
images.caption: This poplar stand at mile 8 is a popular stop for visitors entering from the north entrance.

53.description: When Theodore Roosevelt came to Dakota Territory to hunt bison in 1883, he was a skinny, young, spectacled dude from New York. He could not have imagined how his adventure in this remote and unfamiliar place would forever alter the course of the nation. The rugged landscape and strenuous life that TR experienced here would help shape a conservation policy that we still benefit from today.

images.title: River Bend Overlook, North Unit
images.altText: A colorfully striped butte in the foreground overlooks a dark green badlands landscape
images.caption: The River Bend Overlook offers one of the most popular views in the park's North Unit.

images.title: A View from the Maah Daah Hey Trail
images.altText: the Little Missouri River under blue skies
images.caption: The Maah Daah Hey Trail follows the Little Missouri River for several miles before it enters the Theodore Roosevelt Wilderness.

images.title: Ekblom Trail
images.altText: A muddy river bank lined with cottonwood trees and steep buttes
images.caption: The Ekblom Trail is the gateway to the Theodore Roosevelt Wilderness. All you have to do is make it across the river!

images.title: Raise a Ruckus
images.altText: two bull bison collide heads in a dusty battle for dominance
images.caption: In the summer, bull bison wage furious battles over the right to breed.

images.title: Milky Way
images.altText: the swirling, dusty looking milky way runs vertically though a starry night sky
images.caption: Though light pollution in the area is increasing, the night sky over Theodore Roosevelt National Park remains beautiful and inspiring.

images.credit: NPS Photo / Roland and Lisa Honeyman
images.title: Bison Trail
images.altText: a string of bison are silhouetted against the backdrop of hazy blue and yellow badlands
images.caption: Bison roam the badlands from top to bottom, surprising visitors with their agility and ability to cross even the most rugged terrain.

images.title: Sunset on Buck Hill
images.altText: a green prairie hilltop overlooks the badlands, shrouded in shadows
images.caption: A short climb to the top of Buck Hill in the park's South Unit rewards hikers with a sweeping panorama and a fantastic place to watch the sun rise or set.

images.credit: NPS Photo / Rolan and Lisa Honeyman
images.title: Fall Bugle
images.altText: A bugling bull elk and his harem of cows stand on the edge of a butte as the sunlight fades
images.caption: The ghostly bugles of bull elk can be heard wafting through the badlands in the fall.

images.title: Hoodoos
images.altText: a strange looking sand and rock formation stands in a prairie of brown grass
images.caption: Theodore Roosevelt described the badlands as "so fantastically broken in form and so bizarre in color as to seem hardly properly to belong to this earth."

images.title: Maltese Cross Cabin
images.altText: The rising sun casts light on Roosevelt's snow-covered cabin.
images.caption: Imagine waking up on a crisp winter morning in Roosevelt's Maltese Cross Cabin. It is no wonder that his heart was captured by the romance of life in the West.

54.description: Virgin Islands National Park is more than just beautiful beaches. Hike to historic plantation sites to learn about a time when sugar dominated the island. Visit the ancient petroglyphs carved by the Taino Indians. Come snorkel the coral reefs to discover hidden marine life. Two-thirds of the island of St. John is national park, making it a unique destination for visitors from around the world

images.title: Trunk Bay
images.altText: Turquoise water laps white sandy shore fringed with lush green vegetation.
images.caption: Renowned for its beauty, Trunk Bay is a visitor favorite.

images.title: Queen Angel Fish
images.altText: Queen Angel Fish
images.caption: A Beautiful Queen Angel Fish

images.title: Sunset Bench at Lind Point
images.altText: A sunset colors the horizon as seen from an overlook above the bay.
images.caption: Lind Point Overlook is a perfect spot to enjoy a Virgin Islands sunset.

images.altText: Four Stilts in the Francis Bay Pond
images.caption: Four Stilts in the Francis Bay Pond

images.title: Sunset Paddle
images.altText: A Sunset Paddle
images.caption: A Sunset Paddle, a perfect end to your day.

55.description: Voyageurs is a maze of interconnected water highways. Plan ahead before coming to this water-based park by bringing your own watercraft, reserving a watercraft, or taking a park ranger boat tour.

images.title: Northern Lights
images.altText: Northern Lights over Voyageurs National Park waters
images.caption: Experience the Aurora Borealis at Voyageurs National Park

images.title: Perry Lake
images.altText: overlooking a lake
images.caption: For peace and quiet explore the backcountry of the Kabetogama Peninsula

images.title: Sunset in Voyageurs
images.altText: Orange tinted sky with islands scattered throughout the still lake.
images.caption: Enjoy a sunset in Voyageurs National Park.

images.title: Anderson Bay
images.altText: rock cliffs along the lake
images.caption: Explore the unique geology of Voyageurs National Park and see our story unfold.

images.title: Fall Colors
images.altText: orange, yellow, and green colors are showing in the fall foliage
images.caption: The mix of hardwood and conifers create inspiring scenic views especially in the fall.

images.title: Hike a trail
images.altText: A view of a lake peaks through a stand of pine trees.
images.caption: Get outside and hiking on one of our many trails.

56.description: Rising from the heart of the Tularosa Basin is one of the world's great natural wonders - the glistening white sands of New Mexico. Great wave-like dunes of gypsum sand have engulfed 275 square miles of desert, creating the world's largest gypsum dunefield. White Sands National Park preserves a major portion of this unique dunefield, along with the plants and animals that live here.

images.title: Sunset
images.altText: White dunes in foreground with sun setting behind mountain.
images.caption: Sunsets are one of the most popular times to visit White Sands. Visitors can experience sunset every day of the year.

images.title: Aerial of Dunefield
images.altText: Aerial of white sand dunes.
images.caption: The dunes at White Sands cover 275 square miles of the Tularosa Basin.

images.title: Ripples
images.altText: Close up view of ripples on a dune.
images.caption: The wind shapes and moves the dunes as a whole but gives each individual dune the texture of ripples.

images.title: Fall Colors
images.altText: Cottonwood trees with orange leaves.
images.caption: Fall is a wonderful time to visit as most of our plants with leaves change beautiful colors.

images.title: Shaded Dunes
images.altText: Grey shadows on dunes.
images.caption: As the sun changes its angle through the sky it allows shadow to roll across the dunes.

57.description: Bison, elk, and other wildlife roam the rolling prairie grasslands and forested hillsides of one of America's oldest national parks. Below the remnant island of intact prairie sits Wind Cave, one of the longest and most complex caves in the world. Named for barometric winds at its entrance, this maze of passages is home to boxwork, a unique formation rarely found elsewhere.

images.title: Bison cow and calf
images.altText: a bison cow and calf on the prairie
images.caption: Several hundred bison roam the rolling prairie of Wind Cave National Park.

images.title: Rankin Ridge view
images.altText: rolling hills of forest and prairie landscape
images.caption: Wind Cave National Park from Rankin Ridge, the park's highest point.

images.title: Boxwork
images.altText: criss-cross-patterned calcite fins of the cave feature boxwork
images.caption: Delicate fins of boxwork, a rare cave feature, in Elk's Room, Wind Cave.

images.title: Wind Cave explorer
images.altText: a caver with pads and helmet crawling in the cave
images.caption: Each summer, the Wild Cave Tour offers the chance to get up close and personal with Wind Cave.

images.title: Prairie Dogs
images.altText: two prairie dogs watch from their burrow
images.caption: Prairie dog sightings are common throughout the park's prairies.

58.fullName: Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts
58.description: No matter what your age or taste in shows, you'll find something you like onstage at Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts. From May through September, multiple amphitheaters in the park present performances such as musicals, dance, opera, jazz, and popular and country music. A good time to explore the beauty and history of the park without the crowds is October - April.

images.title: Filene Center Blast Off
images.altText: The Filene Center House full of patrons
images.caption: Everyone is ready to kickoff the Filene Center season.

images.title: Catherine Filene Shouse Bust
images.altText: Bust of Catherine Filene Shouse with building in back
images.caption: Catherine Filene Shouse donated her land to the National Park Service, which Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts was established.

images.title: Junior Ranger Day
images.altText: A ranger swears in two new Jr. Rangers during Jr. Ranger Day activities at the park.
images.caption: Junior Ranger Days occur throughout the summer.

images.title: Dimple Meadow
images.altText: Native garden with the Filene Center in the background
images.caption: In 2012, park staff and volunteers planted 42 species of native grasses and wildflowers here to create a habitat that now supports over 40 kinds of bees and 25 types of butterflies.

images.title: Natural Side of a Park for the Performing Arts
images.altText: Filene Center in the background with autumn leaves
images.caption: There are opportunities year-round to hike and enjoy the outdoors, picnic and participate in ranger programs or walks.

images.title: Children's Theatre-in-the-Woods Performances
images.altText: Sold out show at Theatre-in-the-Woods
images.caption: Most of the activities in the park during the summer are centered around performances at the Filene Center and Theatre-in-the-Woods.

59.fullName: Wrangell - St Elias National Park & Preserve
59.description: Wrangell-St. Elias is a vast national park that rises from the ocean all the way up to 18,008 ft. At 13.2 million acres, the park is the same size as Yellowstone National Park, Yosemite National Park, and Switzerland combined! Within this wild landscape, people continue to live off the land as they have done for centuries. This rugged, beautiful land is filled with opportunities for adventure.

images.title: Icy Bay with Mt. St. Elias
images.altText: Glaciers loom over the ocean with large snowy mountains rising into blue skies
images.caption: Wrangell-St. Elias National Park contains a diversity of natural features.  Landscapes unique to the North American continent are common here.

images.title: Backpackers in Mentasta Mountains
images.altText: Two backpackers sitting in an alpine meadow with snowy mountains in the background
images.caption: Wrangell-St. Elias National Park is a backpacker's paradise.  A variety of routes take you into beautiful country, including the Mentasta Mountains.

images.title: Kennecott Mill Town
images.altText: Historic, large, red buildings with mountains in the background
images.caption: Kennecott Mines National Historic Landmark is found within Wrangell-St. Elias National Park.  This early 1900's copper mining operation overcame numerous challenges and found success in the heart of the Alaskan wilderness.

images.title: Logan Glacier
images.altText: A large glacier with stripes of different colored rock nestled in between barren mountain slopes.
images.caption: Wrangell-St. Elias National Park contains the greatest concentration of glaciers in North America.  More than 3000 glaciers covering over three million acres of land are found in the park.

images.title: Wrangell Mountains
images.altText: Four large snow covered mountains rise above dense forest into blue skies.
images.caption: The Wrangell Mountains dominate the view of the northern half of the park.   This range lies entirely within the park and reaches 16,390 ft (4,996 m) in height.

60.description: On March 1, 1872, Yellowstone became the first national park for all to enjoy the unique hydrothermal wonders. Today, millions of people come here each year to camp, hike, and enjoy the majesty of the park.

images.altText: A crowd of people standing along a wooden boardwalk watches a geyser erupt.
images.caption: Aurum Geyser erupting

61.description: Not just a great valley, but a shrine to human foresight, the strength of granite, the power of glaciers, the persistence of life, and the tranquility of the High Sierra. First protected in 1864, Yosemite National Park is best known for its waterfalls, but within its nearly 1,200 square miles, you can find deep valleys, grand meadows, ancient giant sequoias, a vast wilderness area, and much more.

images.title: Yosemite Falls on a Winter Morning
images.altText: Two tall waterfalls flowing down snow covered granite walls.
images.caption: Yosemite Falls will sometimes only trickle at the end of summer, but wet winters can rejuvenate the flow.

images.title: Cathedral Peak and Lake in Autumn
images.altText: A mountain reflecting in a lake.
images.caption: Cathedral Peak is one of the most recognizable peaks in the Yosemite Wilderness.

images.title: Rainbow over Half Dome
images.altText: A rainbow over a mountain in the distance.
images.caption: A hike up to Sentinel Dome rewards people with great views of the landscape around them.

images.title: Glen Aulin
images.altText: Mountains reflecting in water
images.caption: Glen Auilin is one of five High Sierra Camps, located in the Yosemite high country.

images.title: Tenaya Lake at Sunset
images.altText: Mountains surrounding a lake.
images.caption: Tenaya Lake is a favorite place to stop along the Tioga Road in summer.

images.title: Yosemite Valley from Tunnel View
images.altText: Glaciated valley with vertical cliffs.
images.caption: Tunnel View is perhaps one of the most photographed views in the park.

images.title: Lower Yosemite Fall
images.altText: A waterfall flowing down a granite cliff.
images.caption: The walk to Lower Yosemite Fall is a popular and easy hike.

images.title: Half Dome
images.altText: Granite dome with trace amounts of snow.
images.caption: Half Dome is one of the most recognizable granitic formations in the world.

images.title: El Capitan
images.altText: Massive cliff of El Capitan reflected in the Merced River
images.caption: El Capitan rises over 3,000 feet above the floor of Yosemite Valley.

images.title: Giant Sequoia Trees in the Mariposa Grove of Giant Sequoias
images.altText: Cluster of tall trees with cloudy sky.
images.caption: Yosemite National Park's massive giant sequoias (Sequoiadendron giganteum) live in three groves in the park. The most famous of these is the Mariposa Grove, which contains about 500 mature giant sequoias.

62.description: Follow the paths where ancient native people and pioneers walked. Gaze up at massive sandstone cliffs of cream, pink, and red that soar into a brilliant blue sky. Experience wilderness in a narrow slot canyon. Zion’s unique array of plants and animals will enchant you as you absorb the rich history of the past and enjoy the excitement of present day adventures.

images.title: Temples and Towers of the Virgin
images.altText: A towering sandstone rock formation.
images.caption: The Temples and Towers can be seen from the back patio of the Human History Museum.

images.title: Zion Canyon Visitor Center
images.altText: Zion Canyon Visitor Center with a sandstone peak in the background
images.caption: The Zion Canyon Visitor Center sits near the sandstone peak known as the Watchman

images.title: Mountain of the Sun
images.altText: A white and pink sandstone peak, lit up in the sunlight.
images.caption: The Mountain of the Sun in Zion Canyon.

images.title: The Zion Narrows
images.altText: A narrow canyon with a gentle river flowing in the bottom
images.caption: The Zion Narrows is a challenging wilderness experience.

images.title: Kolob Arch
images.altText: A large red sandstone arch high up on a cliff.
images.caption: Deep in Zion's Wilderness sits Kolob Arch, one of the largest free-standing arches in the world.
